Instead of a complex loop, we’ll use jq to find the current window, grab the next address in the list, and jump to it.

The "No-Fail" Cycle Script
Save this as ~/.config/hypr/scripts/cycle.sh and chmod +x it:

Bash
#!/bin/bash
CLASS=$1

# 1. Get all window addresses for the class in a flat list
# 2. Find the index of the currently active window
# 3. Select the next address in the list (looping back to 0 if at the end)
NEXT_ADDR=$(hyprctl clients -j | jq -r "[.[] | select(.class == \"$CLASS\")] | . as \$list | (index(.[] | select(.focusHistoryID == 0)) + 1) % length | \$list[.].address")

# If a window was found, focus it by address
if [ "$NEXT_ADDR" != "null" ]; then
    hyprctl dispatch focuswindow address:$NEXT_ADDR
fi
Why this works where the last one didn't:
Focus History ID: Instead of comparing raw strings, we use .focusHistoryID == 0, which is Hyprland’s internal way of flagging the currently active window.

JSON Array Indexing: By wrapping the selection in [], we create a stable array. The (index(...) + 1) % length math ensures it cycles infinitely.

Direct Address: Using address:0x... is the most precise way to tell Hyprland which window to focus, bypassing workspace logic entirely.

