Option 2: The Best Script (Clean & Readable)
If you prefer a script file (easier to debug), use this refined version. I've added a fallback so that if Alacritty isn't open, it launches it instead of doing nothing.

File: ~/.config/hypr/scripts/cycle_apps.sh

Bash
#!/bin/bash

CLASS=$1

# Get the address of the next window in the cycle
# 1. Filter by class
# 2. Find the one with focusHistoryID 0 (current)
# 3. Get the next one in the array
NEXT_ADDR=$(hyprctl clients -j | jq -r "
  [.[] | select(.class == \"$CLASS\")] as \$apps
  | if (\$apps | length) == 0 then
      \"LAUNCH\"
    else
      (\$apps | map(.focusHistoryID == 0) | index(true)) as \$idx
      | \$apps[(\$idx + 1) % (\$apps | length)].address
    end")

if [ "$NEXT_ADDR" == "LAUNCH" ]; then
    alacritty &
elif [ "$NEXT_ADDR" != "null" ]; then
    hyprctl dispatch focuswindow address:$NEXT_ADDR
fi
Why this version wins:
Focus History: It uses .focusHistoryID == 0 to identify your current window. This is more reliable than comparing addresses manually.

The Loop: The modulo operator % ensures that when you hit the last Alacritty window, it jumps back to the first one.

The Launch Fallback: If you've closed all your terminals, Meta+A becomes your "Open Terminal" key.

